To display text on an image when hovering over it using ReactJS, follow these basic steps:

1. Create a component for the image and the text overlay that will be displayed when hovering over the image.

```jsx
import React from "react";

function ImageWithOverlay({ src, alt, overlayText }) {
  const [showOverlay, setShowOverlay] = React.useState(false);

  return (
    <div
      onMouseEnter={() => setShowOverlay(true)}
      onMouseLeave={() => setShowOverlay(false)}
      style={{ position: "relative" }}
    >
      <img src={src} alt={alt} />
      {showOverlay && (
        <div
          style={{
            position: "absolute",
            top: 0,
            left: 0,
            backgroundColor: "rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.5)",
            color: "#fff",
            padding: "1rem",
            fontSize: "1.2rem",
          }}
        >
          {overlayText}
        </div>
      )}
    </div>
  );
}

export default ImageWithOverlay;
```

2. Use CSS to add styles to the image container and the text overlay.

```css
/* Style the container */
.ImageWithOverlay {
  position: relative;
}

/* Style the overlay text */
.ImageWithOverlay-overlay {
  position: absolute;
  top: 0;
  left: 0;
  background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.5);
  color: #fff;
  padding: 1rem;
  font-size: 1.2rem;
  opacity: 0;
  transition: opacity 0.3s ease-in-out;
}

/* Show the overlay text on hover */
.ImageWithOverlay:hover .ImageWithOverlay-overlay {
  opacity: 1;
}
```

3. Use the "ImageWithOverlay" component in your app and pass in the necessary props, such as the image source, alt text, and the overlay text that will be displayed.

```jsx
import React from "react";
import ImageWithOverlay from "./ImageWithOverlay";
import imageSrc from "./image.png";

function App() {
  return (
    <div className="App">
      <h1>Example Image with Overlay</h1>
      <ImageWithOverlay
        src={imageSrc}
        alt="Example Image"
        overlayText="This is the overlay text"
      />
    </div>
  );
}

export default App;
```

Note: In this example, we use the "useState" hook to handle the state of showing or hiding the overlay text. Whenever the mouse is entered or left on the image, we change the "showOverlay" state accordingly. We also use basic CSS and "transition" styling to smoothly show or hide the overlay text.

To create a slide in ReactJS, you can use the "react-slick" library. Here are the basic steps to create a simple slide:

1. Install the "react-slick" library using npm/yarn:

```
npm install react-slick
```

2. Import the necessary components, such as "Slider" and "Slide".

```jsx
import React from "react";
import Slider from "react-slick";
import "slick-carousel/slick/slick.css";
import "slick-carousel/slick/slick-theme.css";
```

3. Create a component for the slider and add the necessary settings.

```jsx
function SimpleSlider() {
  const settings = {
    dots: true,
    infinite: true,
    speed: 500,
    slidesToShow: 1,
    slidesToScroll: 1,
  };

  return (
    <Slider {...settings}>
      <div>
        <img src="https://picsum.photos/id/1015/600/400" alt="Slide 1" />
      </div>
      <div>
        <img src="https://picsum.photos/id/1016/600/400" alt="Slide 2" />
      </div>
      <div>
        <img src="https://picsum.photos/id/1018/600/400" alt="Slide 3" />
      </div>
    </Slider>
  );
}
```

4. Render the "SimpleSlider" component in your app.

```jsx
function App() {
  return (
    <div className="App">
      <SimpleSlider />
    </div>
  );
}
```

In this example, we create a basic "SimpleSlider" component that contains three slides with different images. We set the "dots" to true to display navigation dots below the slider and set the "infinite" to true to enable infinite loop scrolling. You can also customize the slider with additional settings such as the speed of the slide transition and the number of slides displayed at a time.

Note: Make sure to import the necessary styles for the slider from the "slick-carousel" package. You can also customize the style of the slider and slides by editing the CSS classes in your stylesheet.

To create an auto-slide in ReactJS, you can use the same "react-slick" library and add some settings to make the slider automatically scroll through the slides. Here are the basic steps to create a simple auto-slide:

1. Install the "react-slick" library using npm/yarn:

```
npm install react-slick
```

2. Import the necessary components, such as "Slider" and "Slide".

```jsx
import React from "react";
import Slider from "react-slick";
import "slick-carousel/slick/slick.css";
import "slick-carousel/slick/slick-theme.css";
```

3. Create a component for the slider and add the necessary settings for auto-slide.

```jsx
function AutoSlider() {
  const settings = {
    dots: true,
    infinite: true,
    speed: 500,
    slidesToShow: 1,
    slidesToScroll: 1,
    autoplay: true,  // enable auto slide
    autoplaySpeed: 2000,  // duration between auto slides in milliseconds
  };

  return (
    <Slider {...settings}>
      <div>
        <img src="https://picsum.photos/id/1015/600/400" alt="Slide 1" />
      </div>
      <div>
        <img src="https://picsum.photos/id/1016/600/400" alt="Slide 2" />
      </div>
      <div>
        <img src="https://picsum.photos/id/1018/600/400" alt="Slide 3" />
      </div>
    </Slider>
  );
}
```

4. Render the "AutoSlider" component in your app.

```jsx
function App() {
  return (
    <div className="App">
      <AutoSlider />
    </div>
  );
}
```

In this example, we create a basic "AutoSlider" component that has the same three slides with different images. We set the "autoplay" to true to enable auto slide and set the "autoplaySpeed" to 2000 milliseconds, which is the duration between the auto slides. You can also use additional settings such as "pauseOnHover" to stop the auto slide when the user hovers over the slider.

Note: Make sure to import the necessary styles for the slider from the "slick-carousel" package. You can also customize the style of the slider and slides by editing the CSS classes in your stylesheet.

To write a single page application (SPA) using JavaScript, you can use frameworks like React, Angular, or Vue. In this example, we will use React to create a basic SPA.

Here are the basic steps to create a simple SPA using React:

1. Install Node.js and create a new React app using the "create-react-app" CLI.

```
npx create-react-app my-spa
```

2. Create a "src/pages" folder and add a new file "Home.js" with the following code:

```jsx
import React from "react";

function Home() {
  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Welcome to my SPA</h1>
    </div>
  );
}

export default Home;
```

3. Create a "src/pages" folder and add a new file "About.js" with the following code:

```jsx
import React from "react";

function About() {
  return (
    <div>
      <h1>About Us</h1>
      <p>We are a company that specializes in creating SPAs.</p>
    </div>
  );
}

export default About;
```

4. Create a "src/components" folder and add a new file "Navbar.js" with the following code:

```jsx
import React from "react";
import { NavLink } from "react-router-dom";

function Navbar() {
  return (
    <nav>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <NavLink exact to="/">
            Home
          </NavLink>
        </li>
        <li>
          <NavLink exact to="/about">
            About
          </NavLink>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </nav>
  );
}

export default Navbar;
```

5. Create a new file "App.js" with the following code:

```jsx
import React from "react";
import { BrowserRouter as Router, Switch, Route } from "react-router-dom";
import Navbar from "./components/Navbar";
import Home from "./pages/Home";
import About from "./pages/About";

function App() {
  return (
    <Router>
      <div className="App">
        <Navbar />
        <Switch>
          <Route path="/about">
            <About />
          </Route>
          <Route path="/">
            <Home />
          </Route>
        </Switch>
      </div>
    </Router>
  );
}

export default App;
```

6. Start the app by running "npm start". Your SPA should now be running on "http://localhost:3000/".

In this example, we created the basic structure of a SPA using React. We created two pages, "Home" and "About", as well as a shared Navbar component. We used React Router to handle the URL routing and switches between pages.

Note: This is a very basic example and you can expand on it by creating more pages and components and incorporating more advanced features such as data fetching and state management.

To transition the position of an image when hovered over in React using CSS, you can add CSS rules to the image component using inline styles:

```jsx
function ImageComponent() {
  const [isHovered, setIsHovered] = React.useState(false);

  const handleMouseEnter = () => {
    setIsHovered(true);
  };

  const handleMouseLeave = () => {
    setIsHovered(false);
  };

  return (
    <img
      src="https://example.com/sample-image.jpg"
      alt="Sample"
      style={{
        position: "relative",
        top: isHovered ? "10px" : "0px",
        transition: "top 0.3s",
      }}
      onMouseEnter={handleMouseEnter}
      onMouseLeave={handleMouseLeave}
    />
  );
}
```

In this example, we use the `useState` hook to manage the hover state of the image. We add two functions to handle the `MouseEnter` and `MouseLeave` events and to update the `isHovered` state accordingly.

We then add inline styles to the image component and set the `position` of the image to `relative` so that we can adjust its top position. We set the `top` property to `10px` when the image is being hovered on and `0px` when not being hovered on using a ternary operator. Finally, we set the `transition` property to `top 0.3s` to animate the transition of the image's position.

Note that this only transitions the position of the image, and does not change the size of the image. If you want to change the size of the image instead of or in addition to the position, you can set the `height` and `width` properties on the image component in the same way.

Sure, in CSS you can use the `:hover` pseudo-class to change the position of an image when hovered over. Here is an example:

```css
img {
  position: relative;
  transition: top 0.3s;
}

img:hover {
  top: 10px;
}
```

In this example, we set the `position` of the image to `relative` so that we can adjust its top position. We also set the `transition` property to `top 0.3s` to animate the transition of the image's position.

Then, using the `:hover` pseudo-class, we set the `top` property of the image to `10px` when it is being hovered on in order to change its position.

You can apply these styles to an HTML `img` tag by adding the `class` attribute to the image tag and setting its value to the corresponding class name:

```html
<img src="image.jpg" alt="Sample" class="image-transition" />
```

Note that this only transitions the position of the image, and does not change the size of the image. If you want to change the size of the image instead of or in addition to the position, you can set the `height` and `width` properties on the `img` tag in the same way.
